Here's an example of how a table of contents (TOC) can be generated automatically in a LaTeX document using the `toc` package:
```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{toc}

\begin{document}

\tableofcontents

\section{Introduction}
This is the introduction section.

\section{Methods}
This section describes the methods used in this study.

\subsection{Data Collection}
This subsection explains how the data was collected.

\subsection{Data Analysis}
This subsection explains how the data was analyzed.

\section{Results}
This section presents the results of the study.

\section{Conclusion}
This section summarizes the conclusions drawn from the study.

\end{document}
```
In this example, we've included the following commands:

1. `\documentclass{article}`: specifies the document class (in this case, an article).
2. `\usepackage{toc}`: loads the `toc` package, which provides support for generating tables of contents.
3. `\begin{document}` and `\end{document}`: mark the beginning and end of the document content.
4. `\tableofcontents`: generates the table of contents. This command should be placed before the first section heading.
5. Section headings (e.g., `\section{Introduction}`): define the sections, subsections, etc. that should be included in the TOC.

When you compile this LaTeX document, it will generate a table of contents automatically, listing each section, subsection, etc. in alphabetical order, along with page numbers. The TOC will appear at the beginning of the document, preceded by the `\tableofcontents` command.

Note: You'll need to compile your LaTeX document twice to generate the TOC correctly. The first compilation will create a `.toc` file, which contains the TOC information. The second compilation will incorporate this information into your document. You can usually achieve this by running `latex` twice on your document file (e.g., `latex mydocument.tex` followed by `latex mydocument.tex` again). Alternatively, you can use a LaTeX editor or IDE that supports automatic compilation and TOC generation, such as TeXstudio or Overleaf.

